{{About|a grammarian of the Lithuanian language||Daniel Klein (disambiguation){{!}}Daniel Klein}}
'''Daniel Klein''' ({{lang-lt|Danielius Kleinas}}) (1609–1666) was a [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] [[pastor]] and scholar from [[Tilsit]], [[Duchy of Prussia]], who is best known for writing the first [[grammar]] book of the [[Lithuanian language]].
Klein studied [[philosophy]], [[theology]], [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] in the [[University of Königsberg]]. In 1637 he became a Lutheran pastor.
In 1653 Klein published the first grammar book of the Lithuanian language (''Grammatica Litvanica''), written in [[Latin]]. Klein coined the distinctive Lithuanian letter [[Ė]].<ref>{{DOClink|[http://www.euro-languages.net/lithuania/upload/files/euro_languages_lt_25.doc The Lithuanian Language: Traditions and Trends, Giedrius Subačius]|1.5 MB}}</ref> He also wrote a Lithuanian dictionary, but it was left unpublished.
Klein published collections of Lithuanian [[hymn]]s (Lit. ''giesmes''), some of which he wrote himself.
