'''Olous''' or '''Olus''' ([[Ancient Greek]]: {{lang|grc|Ὄλους}},<ref>[[Scylax|Scyl.]] p. 19, [[Xenion]], ''ap.'' [[Stephanus of Byzantium|Steph. B.]] s. v.</ref><ref>[[Ptolemy|Ptol.]] iii. 17. § 5</ref> or {{lang|grc|Ὄλουλις}}<ref>Stadiasm. 350</ref>) is an ancient, sunken city situated at the present day town of [[Elounda]], [[Crete]], [[Greece]].
==History== After continuing boundary disputes with the hillfort of [[Lato]],<ref>[http://themodernantiquarian.com/site/10847/lato.html#fieldnotes C.Michael Hogan, ''Lato Fieldnotes'', The Modern Antiquarian, Jan 10, 2008]</ref> the citizens of Olous eventually entered into a treaty with those of Lato.<ref>[[Wilhelm Dittenberger|Dittenberger]], Syll.&#179;, No. 712 - [http://www.attalus.org/docs/sig2/s712.html English translation].</ref> There was a temple to [[Britomartis]] in the city, a wooden statue of whom was erected by [[Daedalus]], the mythical ancestor of the Daedalidae, and father of Cretan art.<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausan.]] ix. 40. § 3.</ref> Her [[effigy]] is represented on the coins of Olous.<ref>[[Eckhel]], vol. ii. p. 316; Théodore Edme Mionnet, ''Descr.'' vol. ii. p. 289; Combe, ''Mus. Hunter.''</ref>
==Present conditions== [[Archaeologists]] discovered ancient texts within the ruins linking the town with the ancient cities of [[Knossos]] and the island of [[Rhodes]].<ref>[http://www.attalus.org/docs/seg/s23_547.html SEG_23.547] - treaty between Rhodes and Olous.</ref> The sunken city can be visited by tourists swimming in Elounda Bay. Today, the only visible remnants of the city are some scattered wall bases.
