'''Omry Ronen''' (born '''Imre Szörényi''') (July 12, 1937 in [[Odessa]]&nbsp;– November 1, 2012 in [[Ann Arbor]]) was an American [[Slavist]], known for his works on the [[Silver Age of Russian Poetry]] and especially on the poetry of [[Osip Mandelstam]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Рюхель|first=Федор|script-title=ru:РОНЕН, Омри|language=Russian|url=http://www.ruthenia.ru/moskva/encycl/r/ronen.htm}}</ref>
==Biography== Ronen was born in Odessa in 1937 into a [[Hungarian people|Hungarian]] [[Jewish]] family. His father was the biochemist Emerich (Imre) Szörényi (January 12, 1905&nbsp;– January 17, 1959), known for his work on muscle physiology. From 1934 to 1953, the family lived in the Soviet Union, where Emerich Szörényi headed the tissue protein research department of the Institute of Biochemistry and the biochemistry department of the Institute of Microbiology of the Ukrainian Academy of Sciences. In 1950, he was appointed head of the newly established Institute of Biochemistry in Hungary, however, he was only able to return to Hungary with his family in 1953.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.matud.iif.hu/2010/12/09.htm|journal=Magyar Tudomány|title=A HATVANÉVES MTA ENZIMOLÓGIAI INTÉZET ELSŐ ÉVTIZEDE|last=Orosz|first=Ferenc}}</ref>
Ronen started his undergraduate studies in [[Budapest University]].<ref name=cv>{{cite web|url=http://www.lsa.umich.edu/UMICH/slavic/Home/People/Faculty/Ronen%20CV%202009%20PDF.pdf|title=CV|publisher=University of Michigan}}</ref> He took part in the [[1956 Hungarian Revolution]], and fled to Israel after the uprising was suppressed.<ref name="obituary">{{cite web|url=https://lsa.umich.edu/slavic/news-events/all-news/archived-news/2012/11/in-memoriam--professor-omry-ronen.html|title=In Memoriam: Professor Omry Ronen|last1=Eagle|first1=H|last2=Maiorova|first2=O|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> He obtained his B.A. in linguistics and English literature from [[Hebrew University]] and his PhD in Slavic languages and literatures from [[Harvard]].<ref name=obituary/><ref name=huji>{{cite web|url=http://www.huji.ac.il/dataj/controller/ihoker/MOP-STAFF_LINK?sno=901&Save_t=|title=Department page| publisher=Hebrew University}}</ref> From 1972 to 1985, he was professor at [[Hebrew University]]. In 1985 he became a Professor of Slavic Languages and Literatures at the [[University of Michigan]], [[Ann Arbor]] where he remained until his death.<ref name=obituary/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lsa.umich.edu/slavic/people/faculty|title=Faculty list|publisher=University of Michigan}}</ref>
==Work== The works of Omry Ronen on the Silver Age of Russian Poetry include {{harvtxt|Ronen|1983}} and {{harvtxt|Ronen|2000}}. Ronen also made important contributions to the study of [[Alexander Pushkin|Pushkin]]'s poetics, the poetry of the [[Oberiu]], [[Vladimir Nabokov]], and numerous other topics.<ref name=obituary/>
Ronen is also the author of three books of essays based on his column "From the Town of Ann” in the journal [[Zvezda (magazine)|"Zvezda"]].<ref name=obituary/>
